        "client_msg_id": "6dde971e-1afe-43ad-b178-797ee9db5ab7",
        "type": "message",
        "text": "How do folks handle the fee structure\/contract when you have multiple projects assigned to one writer?\n\nFor example, I hired a writer to work on a fixed number of blog posts, and we have written a contract for that project. However, we really like the writers' work, and I've expanded the scope of his contract to work with me on a series of 4 \"thought leadership\" pieces written by my ceo. I am also considering them for a case study.\n\nThese two projects, by their very nature, are different in scope - the blog posts required him to get a rough outline from our team, him to do some research, and then deliver the post.\n\nThe \"thought leadership\" pieces require several calls with my CEO, taking copy I've written, going through multiple revisions of the posts (3-4 rounds) and finally getting his partner (a trained editor) to review the post before submission.\n\nI am trying to decide if I should re-open our previous contract and have two separate projects - \"blog posts\" and \"thought leadership\" or create a totally new contract. I welcome input\/advice from this group.",
